review:
I have not played TF1. So it was immediately apparent to me what game heavily inspired this installment. Thousands of fans of Transport Tycoon Deluxe will instantly and heartedly recognize the gameplay mechanics down to the minute detail. So much so I tend to think of TF2 as "TTD remade with modern and better visuals". And indeed the visuals are stunning, but, frankly, only in comparison with the original TTD. You have got the true 3D, smooth terrain, no grid, vehicle front camera view, wildlife, pedestrians, animated industries, car traffic etc -- all that was previously left for imagination.

There are, however, certain decisions in TF2 design we fans with hundreds of OpenTTD playtime experience will find dubious at best. The TF2 gameplay in general is very rough and a bit far from polished logic, complexity and capabilities of craftily modded OpenTTD. The following is the list of such technicalities that made me squirm.
* You can not make stations into hubs, that is, place a bus terminal and a train station adjacent to an airport and work with it as a single station; also you can not assign a tram to stop at an airport or a passenger train station;
* Sending vehicle into depot makes it forget what line it was working on before that; also you can not skip stations in the schedule;
* Semaphores/traffic lights are dumb and are only good in making simple -O- loops;
* There is no obvious way to build a bridge or tunnel wherever I want as was in TTD; you have to manipulate terrain in a very specific way which is not too easy since it is now smooth in geometry and in elevation as well; short bridges/tunnels are not possible at all;
* For reasons unknown, assigned routes must include not only station, but a platform too; this make it hard to connect two doubletracked stations by double track without crossings and keep two trains running same schedule; this essentially forces you to join tracks before the route enters the station at either end and place a bunch of semaphores;
* For the same unknown reason the cargo waiting on the station for Line A train can not be picked by the Line B train even if that will make your logistics more efficient;
* There are only three loading actions available -- load if any, full load any, full load all; No unload?
* Carriages age separately from the engines;
* The pricing of the engines is outrageous, even if more realistic;
* You can sell a vehicle in a mid-flight or mid-transit between stations without having it in depot;

This list is far from complete, it only includes what I remember after a several days of casual play.
Still I can assert that TF2 has made a good attempt at replicating and enriching the elegant OpenTTD aesthetics but there is a lot of work still to do.

Definitely recommend, especially for OpenTTD fans.

Some 100 hours in and I can say - good job (5 of 10 poits).
Pros.:
- mods;
- mods are free (unlike those for Assetto Corssa);
- so far no DLC content (puzling why not);
- better graphics.
Cons.:
Base game is like cheap food sold as AAA experience and feels almost like an EA game. 
- dependancy on mods;
- constant game and sound crashes;
- bad or abcent system optimization for biger maps;
- graphical misses (expl.: the renders - you need mods again);
- misleading system requirements or rather not complete picture of what you should have. I suspect that the recomanded are somewhere in the vecinity of a i7 or i9 9000 series, 40~64 GB RAM, 8~12GB VGA power... 

Do I recommend the game? Yes, there is no better substitute for the modelin hobby in a digital form. The modding community is bigger than ever (lots of customization). The price is off, but Steam loves sale days.
